WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.280
Hi, so I'm super excited to be here.

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:17.360
So when I was starting college, I was super excited, because I was going to be doing math

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:18.680
and science.

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:24.040
And I would just get to work with equations and numbers and do experiments and play with

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:30.080
liquid nitrogen, and I would never have to write anything ever again.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:34.360
And I managed to make it through, I would say, a lot of my undergraduate career without

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:41.860
that being too incorrect, which might say something about my scientific education.

00:00:41.860 --> 00:00:47.200
But when I got to graduate school, I quickly realized that you couldn't just do the science,

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:50.639
you actually also had to talk about it.

00:00:50.639 --> 00:00:57.880
And an excellent talk here in this room yesterday by Lewis Kervin, sometimes you just need words.

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:04.120
So I was super fortunate to have some mentors who helped me learn how to write and communicate,

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:05.940
tell a narrative.

00:01:05.940 --> 00:01:09.879
So I turned the corner, and I'm okay with writing now.

00:01:09.879 --> 00:01:13.599
I've got a lot more practice at it.

00:01:13.599 --> 00:01:19.760
So much so now that if you work with me, one of the things as a part of onboarding to work

00:01:19.879 --> 00:01:25.760
with me is that Hadley will tell someone that my love language is Google Docs.

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:31.279
So as the open source program director at RStudio, now pause it, if you work with me,

00:01:31.279 --> 00:01:32.959
expect to see a lot of Google Docs.

00:01:32.959 --> 00:01:37.760
Great to have just met you, Elliot, expect some Google Docs.

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:41.680
So I'm pretty squared away on that.

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:46.059
But there's still presentations, and I do like talking about ideas.

00:01:46.059 --> 00:01:49.320
So I'll submit the talk, I'm super excited about it.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:51.239
I'll even write the talk.

00:01:51.239 --> 00:01:55.639
And then when it comes to doing the slides, I am never excited.

00:01:55.639 --> 00:01:58.559
I'm never thinking like, oh, this is going to be great.

00:01:58.559 --> 00:02:02.599
I'm going to sit down to do my slides, I'll be able to put stuff right where I want it

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:08.440
on the slide, my data and code, I'll just be able to integrate it seamlessly into my

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:09.440
slides.

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:13.839
And if I make any changes, no big deal, it'll just automatically update.

00:02:13.839 --> 00:02:19.360
That has not once been a thought that has gone through my mind.

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:20.919
Until now.

00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:22.360
Until Quarto.

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:30.639
So Quarto is making presentations fun again, or for me at least, for the first time.

00:02:30.639 --> 00:02:35.440
I am so excited about Quarto that I would sing about it, but that is not an area of

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:38.240
strength for me.

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:46.919
So instead, I have the words to favorite things, and I'm going to revise these words for Quarto.

00:02:46.919 --> 00:02:52.360
So you may be familiar with this component of the song.

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:59.440
Again, not an area of strength, but it's kind of a good tune, so I might accidentally sing.

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:05.679
So raindrops on roses and whiskers on kittens, bright copper kettles and warm woolen mittens,

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:10.720
brown paper packages tied up with string, these are a few of my favorite things.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:16.119
I do like most of those things, but I do also like Quarto.

00:03:16.119 --> 00:03:18.440
So raindrops on roses.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:23.919
Instead of raindrops on roses, I am going to talk about visual edits.

00:03:23.919 --> 00:03:28.759
So I mentioned one of the things that I found frustrating is that I couldn't, like, figure

00:03:28.759 --> 00:03:31.479
out where I'm going to put stuff on my slides.

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:37.360
So this is a very straightforward slide, list item one, two, three, but what I want

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:42.860
to show you is how I did this when I was creating this slide.

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:45.479
So I have my code here.

00:03:45.479 --> 00:03:52.360
Is this video going to play?

00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:53.360
There we go.

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:54.360
Okay.

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:55.360
So I can switch to visual.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:58.800
I can see it here as source or as visual.

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:03.639
I can add in my list item here, switch back to source.

00:04:03.639 --> 00:04:06.119
There it is as source.

00:04:06.119 --> 00:04:10.479
And then if I render it, it's going to render right here in preview.

00:04:10.479 --> 00:04:15.440
So I can really integrate where I'm writing my code and being able to see things right

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:16.440
away.

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:21.600
So that's a really big deal for me, because that's how I put my slides together.

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:23.799
All right.

00:04:23.799 --> 00:04:25.559
Whiskers on kittens.

00:04:25.559 --> 00:04:28.519
Kittens are one of my favorites.

00:04:28.519 --> 00:04:32.200
But one of my other favorites is columns and tables.

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:35.959
So again, when you're thinking about how to construct your slides, how you lay things

00:04:35.959 --> 00:04:38.399
out is really important.

00:04:38.399 --> 00:04:43.119
So if I'm thinking, oh, what are some of my other favorite things besides Cordo, ice cream

00:04:43.119 --> 00:04:49.320
is top of the list, R and Python, I do like both, I'm so excited about Posit.

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:54.160
Least favorite things, banana flavor, fine as a banana, not a good flavor in anything

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:55.160
else.

00:04:55.160 --> 00:04:57.200
I know people have different opinions.

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:02.040
Slamming doors, nails on chalkboards, locking keys in the car, to refer to Julia and Max's,

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:03.040
I have done that.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:05.040
I still fear it, actually.

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:06.040
Okay.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:11.200
So what if I wanted to add another column, put in an image?

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:12.200
No big deal.

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:17.519
And when I say no big deal, let's take a look at the code that goes along with columns.

00:05:17.519 --> 00:05:18.519
This is pretty straightforward.

00:05:18.519 --> 00:05:21.880
We have, hey, we're going to do some columns.

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:26.079
And then we have the columns and the information that's in them.

00:05:26.079 --> 00:05:29.200
We can also change the column width super easily.

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:32.440
So there's a lot of flexibility in how we put things together.

00:05:32.440 --> 00:05:37.279
And again, combined with that visual editor, let's try some stuff out, see how it looks.

00:05:37.279 --> 00:05:42.720
I would almost say, like, I've never had sort of this much power of placement in my slides

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:47.880
unless it was, like, HTML tables, but I know we're not supposed to compare things to HTML,

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:51.880
so forget I said that.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:52.880
So tables.

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:59.920
Tables are another thing that has never been a joyful experience in my presentation creation.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:00.920
So this is a table.

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:08.799
I took some data from scraped reviews of ice cream from a few different websites, and which

00:06:08.799 --> 00:06:11.839
are the most favorite ice cream flavors.

00:06:11.839 --> 00:06:14.720
So I took this data, and I put it into a table.

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:16.839
This is just a cable table.

00:06:16.839 --> 00:06:22.359
So really not a lot of complexity to this table, but integrates straight in with my

00:06:22.359 --> 00:06:24.799
slides.

00:06:24.799 --> 00:06:26.480
I can do a GT table.

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:31.239
So this is GT, a little cooler looking, has a little bit of color, better formatting.

00:06:31.239 --> 00:06:36.920
These are really some of the, like, fundamental things around GT.

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:39.480
I'm not using all the fancy features here.

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:42.679
But everything that's here is possible for you.

00:06:42.679 --> 00:06:47.679
So what I really love about any system, when we talk about, like, being code first and

00:06:47.679 --> 00:06:51.320
people are talking about the UI, is what this makes possible.

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:56.000
So, like, where you can start and then where you can go with things is, like, only limited

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.679
by your imagination and how much time you want to spend formatting.

00:07:00.679 --> 00:07:01.679
Okay.

00:07:01.679 --> 00:07:03.320
So great.

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:06.200
My slides are doing great.

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:09.040
Now I'm going to have to give my presentation.

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:11.239
So bright copper kettles.

00:07:11.239 --> 00:07:12.239
I like kettles.

00:07:12.239 --> 00:07:13.239
I like wine.

00:07:13.239 --> 00:07:14.239
I guess I like tea.

00:07:14.239 --> 00:07:17.760
I had to look up what a copper kettle was, actually.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:20.160
But notes for the speaker.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.119
So that's another thing that you want as a presenter.

00:07:23.119 --> 00:07:26.880
So I did mention I don't love the presentation component.

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:31.000
So when I'm putting together a talk, I actually start with the notes.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:35.320
And so it's really nice to be able to have those notes there for me and then build the

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:39.119
slides actually kind of in the reverse order.

00:07:39.119 --> 00:07:45.519
So here's just a regular slide, a slide with speaker notes, a slide content.

00:07:45.519 --> 00:07:50.279
This is the code that would generate that slide.

00:07:50.279 --> 00:07:53.600
And then this is what it looks like to me as a speaker.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:08:00.239
So I have the slide that I'm talking about, then I have the time, and then I have in that

00:08:00.239 --> 00:08:04.679
bottom right where the speaker notes go, and then my next slide.

00:08:04.679 --> 00:08:08.440
Everything that you would hope for as a speaker.

00:08:08.440 --> 00:08:13.480
And again, I just really appreciate how it's all integrated into one document.

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:18.299
So you're really working just like start to finish in one place.

00:08:18.299 --> 00:08:22.959
And not having a context switch has been a really nice feature.

00:08:22.959 --> 00:08:25.200
Okay.

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:28.559
And next, we have warm woolen mittens.

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:29.839
I like warm woolen mittens.

00:08:29.839 --> 00:08:32.340
My hands are always cold.

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:34.440
So code first keeps things stable.

00:08:34.440 --> 00:08:39.200
It's a bit of a stretch, I had to run.

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:45.880
But this is really about what I referred to at the beginning around the idea of reproducibility.

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:52.559
So as Garrick mentioned in my introduction, I spent many years teaching people about how

00:08:52.559 --> 00:08:57.400
to work with data, a code, and a research context, good practices.

00:08:57.400 --> 00:09:04.320
And so the reproducibility component is essential when we're thinking about scientific communication.

00:09:05.239 --> 00:09:11.559
And so within Quoro, the slides, the figure, and the code, they're all integrated.

00:09:11.559 --> 00:09:16.880
And so I've had situations where I've put together a presentation, and I had a figure

00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:17.880
in that presentation.

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:22.640
I wanted to use that figure again, but I couldn't actually remember how I had generated that

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:24.280
figure.

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:26.080
We don't have that problem here, right?

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:27.719
It's all integrated together.

00:09:27.719 --> 00:09:33.320
And so I think about sharing things with collaborators, but I also especially think about sharing

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:40.400
things with future me, because I don't necessarily remember what past me did, and past me doesn't

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:42.979
always make good choices.

00:09:42.979 --> 00:09:49.440
And so the more I can document, the more things are integrated, the easier it makes to reproduce

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:55.719
things, to share, to communicate effectively and accurately what we're doing, especially

00:09:55.719 --> 00:09:57.919
in a research context.

00:09:57.919 --> 00:10:06.320
So we can see here, again, this is just straightforward ggplot code, and then here we have the graph

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:10.640
that this code generates here below, just all right together.

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:16.080
So in general, right, I wouldn't show the code necessarily along with the figure.

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:21.080
But now, if you go get the slides, you have right there the code that went into the figure.

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:25.359
There's no questions about what it was that I was communicating in this talk.

00:10:25.359 --> 00:10:29.880
And you probably really want to know the relationship between the average star rating

00:10:29.880 --> 00:10:32.799
and numbers of reviews in ice cream flavors.

00:10:32.799 --> 00:10:36.719
I wouldn't say there's really any positive particular trends here.

00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:40.039
I wouldn't do a statistical analysis.

